1}}, {"id": ["mesh:D000450"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "aldosterone", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9991336464881897, "span": {"begin": 443, "end": 454}}, {"id": ["mesh:D003900"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "deoxycorticosterone", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9995542168617249, "span": {"begin": 460, "end": 479}}, {"id": ["mesh:D002244"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "carbon", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9835537672042847, "span": {"begin": 565, "end": 571}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:29239"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "hydride", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9994755387306213, "span": {"begin": 610, "end": 617}}, {"id": ["mesh:D002244"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "carbon", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9913536906242371, "span": {"begin": 627, "end": 633}}, {"id": ["mesh:D002244"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "carbon", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9984968900680542, "span": {"begin": 665, "end": 671}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:57783"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "NADPH", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9996709823608398, "span": {"begin": 713, "end": 718}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:6716"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "5&alpha;-reductase type 2", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9954970479011536, "span": {"begin": 847, "end": 872}}, {"id": ["mesh:D013739"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "testosterone", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9984613656997681, "span": {"begin": 909, "end": 921}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "5&alpha", "obj": "DNA", "prob": 0.5156562328338623, "span": {"begin": 1066, "end": 1073}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:6715"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "5&alpha;-reductase", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9926526546478271, "span": {"begin": 1066, "end": 1084}}], "text": "This KE describes the inhibition of 5&alpha;-reductases (3-oxo-5&alpha;-steroid 4-dehydrogenases). These enzymes are widely expressed in tissues of both sexes and responsible for conversion of steroid hormones.  There are three isozymes: 5&alpha;-reductase type 1, 2, and 3. The substrates for 5&alpha;-reductases are 3-oxo (3-keto), &Delta;4,5 C19/C21 steroids such as testosterone, progesterone, androstenedione, epi-testosterone, cortisol, aldosterone, and deoxycorticosterone. The enzymatic reaction leads to an irreversible breakage of the double bond between carbon 4 and 5 and subsequent insertion of a hydride anion at carbon 5 and insertion of a proton at carbon 4. The reaction is aided by the cofactor NADPH. The substrate affinity and reaction velocity differ depending on the combination of substrate and enzyme isoform, for instance 5&alpha;-reductase type 2 has a higher substrate affinity for testosterone than the type 1 isoform of the enzyme, and the enzymatic reaction occurs at a higher velocity under optimal conditions. Likewise, inhibitors of 5&alpha;-reductase may exhibit differential effects depending on isoforms (Azzouni et al., 2012).", "timestamp": "Fri May 15 21:37:04 +0000 2026"}